            "title": "OpenAI says China's DeepSeek trained its AI by distilling US models: memo",
            "description": "<div class=\"txt-s4 article-text\"><p>STORY: OpenAI has warned U.S. lawmakers that Chinese AI startup DeepSeek is targeting the ChatGPT maker and the nation's leading AI companies.</p><p>\n              To replicate models and use them for its own training.</p><!-- Article --><p>\n              That's according to a memo seen by Reuters.</p><p>\n              Sam Altman-led OpenAI accused DeepSeek of, quote, \"ongoing efforts to free-ride on the capabilities developed by OpenAI and other U.S. frontier labs.\"</p><p>\n              The technique is known as distillation.</p><p>\n              It involves having an older, more established and powerful AI model evaluate the quality of the answers coming out of a newer model.</p><p>\n              And effectively transfers the older model's learnings.</p><p>\n              The memo was sent to the U.S. House Select Committee on Strategic Competition between the U.S. and the Chinese Communist Party on Thursday.</p><p>\n              DeepSeek and its parent company High-Flyer did not immediately respond to Reuters' requests for comment.</p><p>\n              China's DeepSeek shook markets early last year with a set of AI models that rivaled some of the best offerings from the U.S.,.</p><p>\n              It fuelled concerns in Washington that China could catch up in the AI race despite restrictions.</p></div>",
            "link": "https://hk.marketscreener.com/news/openai-says-china-s-deepseek-trained-its-ai-by-distilling-us-models-memo-ce7e5ddadf8ff32c",
            "pub_date": "2026-02-13 23:07:39",
            "source": "marketscreener",
